So, thunks should avoid multiple evaluation, too, and handle exceptions in a way that is relatively coherent. I like:<p><pre><code>  function thunk(f) { 
    var evaluated = false;
    var value = undefined;
    var excepting = undefined;
    return { force: function () {
      if (!evaluated) {
        evaluated = true; 
        try { value = f(); } catch (e) { excepting = e; }
      }
      if (excepting) throw excepting;
      return value;
    }}
  }</code></pre>
